column65:
While most leisure venues (indoor casinos, indoor skating rinks, indoor play areas, bowling alleys and conference centres and exhibition halls) reopened nationally on August 15, they were not reopened in North of England, including this region. 

The August 15 legislation states: 
"Regulation 2(7) and (12) makes provision inserting Regulation 7A and the Schedule into the North of England Regulations which maintain the closure of the following businesses and venues in the protected area: (...)
d. Casinos;
e. Indoor skating rinks;
f. Indoor play areas, including soft play areas;
g. Bowling alleys; and"

On September 8, these were permitted to reopen except for in Bolton. The SI 1019 (2020) explanatory note states "to allow the opening of certain businesses and leisure facilities in the areas covered by those Regulations."

On October 23, Greater Manchester was subjected to restrictions closing: "
(a)betting shops and adult gaming centres;

(b)casinos;

(c)bingo halls;

(d)soft play areas and soft play centres.

column62:
On Oct 24, heightened measures were introduced for Tier 3 areas in Greater Manchester. (Note that the Wiki says Oct 23, but the legislation says that the relevant regulation (4)(6)(e) came into force on Oct 24.)

Quote from Oct 24 legislation:

"Greater Manchester

3.—(1) The businesses and services in this sub-paragraph are restricted businesses and restricted services in those areas listed in Schedule 2 in relation to Greater Manchester—

(a)betting shops and adult gaming centres;

(b)casinos;

(c)bingo halls;

(d)soft play areas and soft play centres.

(2) Paragraph 17(1) of Schedule 1 and sub-paragraph (1)(d) do not prevent the use of soft play areas by persons with a disability within the meaning of paragraph 11(4) of Schedule 1."
